<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911111-0116</DOCNO><DOCID>911111-0116.</DOCID><HL>   McDonnell Douglas to Cut   1,500 Transport-Plane Jobs</HL><DATE>11/11/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   MD</CO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)</IN><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)MISSOURI (MO)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   LONG BEACH, Calif. -- McDonnell Douglas Corp. said itplans to cut employment by about 1,500 at its transportaircraft division over the next few weeks.   The aircraft maker said notices will be handed out toworkers at several factory sites, including Long Beach. Thedivision, which is based here, has about 42,000 employees andhas already reduced its ranks by about 9,000 in the past 15months. Overall, McDonnell Douglas currently has about112,000 employees.</LP><TEXT>   A McDonnell Douglas spokesman said the cuts werenecessary, in part, because of &quot;softness&quot; in the commercialairliner market. As reported, the company is now planning tosteady production of its MD-11 jetliner at about 40 a year,down from the 60 or so originally envisioned. McDonnellDouglas also will scale back its MD-80 production to about100 jets next year from 140 this year, the spokesman said.   In addition, the spokesman said, some workers on the C-17military cargo-plane line would be affected.</TEXT></DOC>